Part a):

From the figures below, we can see that the Hidden Gem Score is clearly associated with both Runtime Category and Languages Used in the Film.

#First, we want to create a new tibble with just the variables that we care about: 1) Hidden Gem Score 2) Runtime Category 3) Languages Used in the Film

data_filtered_task1a <- data_filtered %>% select(Title, Languages, Runtime, `Hidden Gem Score`)
 
#########################

#Then, compare the association between Runtime Category and Hidden Gem Score
data_filtered_task1a_runtime <- data_filtered_task1a %>% select(Title, Runtime, `Hidden Gem Score`) %>% drop_na() #Drop NA values
ggplot(data_filtered_task1a_runtime, aes(x=Runtime,y=`Hidden Gem Score`)) + stat_boxplot(geom="errorbar",width=0.25) + geom_boxplot() +
xlab("Runtime") + ylab("Hidden Gem Score")

#########################

#Then, compare the association between Languages and Hidden Gem Score
#First, we want to rearrange the data tibble such that each language used in the data are separated into different rows.
data_filtered_task1a_languages <- data_filtered_task1a %>% select(Title, Languages, `Hidden Gem Score`) %>% drop_na() #Drop NA values
data_filtered_task1a_langseparated <- separate_rows(data_filtered_task1a_languages, Languages)

#Now, what I want to plot is a bar graph of the mean Hidden Gem Score for each language. 
#First, let us generate a summary tibble with the mean Hidden Gem Score:
hidden_gem_score_summary <- data_filtered_task1a_langseparated %>% group_by(Languages) %>% summarise(mean = mean(`Hidden Gem Score`))
ggplot(hidden_gem_score_summary, aes(x=reorder(Languages, -mean),y=mean)) + geom_bar(stat="identity") + labs(x="Language", y="Mean Hidden Gem Score") + theme(axis.text.x=element_blank(), axis.ticks.x=element_blank())

Part b):

From the plots and lines of best fits below, we can see that the three review sites are all strongly correlated with the Hidden Gem Score.

data_filtered_task1b <- data_filtered %>% select(Title, `IMDb Score`, `Rotten Tomatoes Score`, `Metacritic Score`, `Hidden Gem Score`)

ggplot(data_filtered_task1b %>% select(Title, `IMDb Score`, `Hidden Gem Score`) %>% drop_na(), aes(x=`IMDb Score`, y=`Hidden Gem Score`)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)

ggplot(data_filtered_task1b %>% select(Title, `Rotten Tomatoes Score`, `Hidden Gem Score`) %>% drop_na(), aes(x=`Rotten Tomatoes Score`,y=`Hidden Gem Score`)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)

ggplot(data_filtered_task1b %>% select(Title, `Metacritic Score`, `Hidden Gem Score`) %>% drop_na(), aes(x=`Metacritic Score`,y=`Hidden Gem Score`)) + geom_point() + geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE)

Part c):

Yes, the hidden gem score increased over time, especially for longer films.

data_filtered_task1c <- data_filtered %>% select(Title, Runtime, `Release Date`, `Hidden Gem Score`)
data_filtered_dropped_task1c <- data_filtered_task1c %>% drop_na() #Drop NA values

#Now, we want to generate a summary tibble such that a mean Hidden Gem Score is calculated for each year.
data_filtered_dropped_task1c <- data_filtered_dropped_task1c %>% mutate(`Release Date` = as.numeric(format(`Release Date`,'%Y'))) #Replace Release Date with the year only

data_filtered_dropped_GroupedRuntime_task1c <- data_filtered_dropped_task1c %>% group_by(Runtime) #Group by runtime for plotting below

ggplot(data_filtered_dropped_GroupedRuntime_task1c, aes(x=`Release Date`, y=`Hidden Gem Score`, fill=Runtime)) + facet_wrap(~Runtime) + 
  geom_bar(stat="identity") + theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=90, hjust=1))
